<div id="nodeDecoration"><div id="headerContent"><h1 id="nodeTitle">3.4 Third conditional</h1></div></div>
<div class="iDevice_wrapper FreeTextIdevice" id="id255">
<div class="iDevice emphasis0">
<div id="ta255_85" class="block iDevice_content">
<p>If + past perfect, ... would have + past participle</p>
<p><em>Ex: If I had woken up early, I would have caught the train</em></p>
<p>It is used to express something which did not happen in the past and its results which are imaginary:</p>
<p><em>If he hadn</em>’<em>t been watching TV until late, he wouldn</em>’<em>t have overslept.</em></p>
<p>Sometimes we can use could or might instead of would. In that case, the meaning of the sentences may change:</p>
<p><em>If we had trained harder we could have won the competition (they had the ability but they didn</em>’<em>t train)</em></p>
<p><em>If we had trained harder we would have won the competition (they would have won for sure, but they didn</em>’<em>t train enough)</em></p>
<p><em>If we had bought a car, we might have gone on a road trip (the trip was a possibility)</em></p>
<p><em>If we had bought a car, we would have gone on a road trip (the trip was a certainty)</em></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
